	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB3538_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: I started my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560" type="subject">labour service</term> on <date when="1942-05-11">May
					11, 1942</date> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3044154/suelysap.html">Tápiósüly</placeName> where we dug sewers
				standing in the chest-high water. Moreover after work we had <q><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562"
						type="subject">exercise</term></q> too. It was forbidden to have visiting <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-820" type="subject">family members</term> and so was obtaining <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> through them. If despite of this we
				managed to get some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> then <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Lieutenant</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_koszegi">Kőszegi</persName> punished us in the cruellest way: he compelled us to do <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">exercise</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">trussed</term> people up. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Sergeant</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_forgacs">Forgács</persName> urged us to <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> by shooting around our feet and hitting us with a rifle.
				butt. From here we were taken to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3047669/nagykata.html">Nagykáta</placeName> where <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Lieutenant Colonel</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_muray">Muray</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">tortured</term> people and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">hit</term> us in the face because the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">yellow star</term> was never sewn on our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> in a proper way. Fifty-five of us were
				crammed into a very <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">small room</term>; it was
				impossible to even move. We could <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">wash
					ourselves</term> only in the canal. We had a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>lance sergeant</term> (unfortunately I do not know his name, all I know is that he used to be a barber in the Pajor <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Budapest</placeName>), who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">kicked and beat</term> people and did not allow us to
				report as <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term>. From <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3047669/nagykata.html">Nagykáta</placeName> we were taken to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/690791/ukraine.html">Ukraine</placeName>. When we arrived at the station, the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1077" type="subject">Hungarian soldiers</term> who were leaving for home
				made the following remark: <q>They aren’t coming back for sure...</q></p>
			<p><pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB3538_02.jpg"/> The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject"
					>deputy commander</term> of the company was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject"
					>Warrant Officer</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_leidl">Leidl</persName>, who talked to the men in the rudest tone. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Lance Sergeant</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_bajor">Bajor</persName> (a worker from a <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html"
					>Pest</placeName> brick <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject">factory</term>)<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject"> </term><term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat</term> the people all the time and told us many
				times that we were all going to perish. When we came home from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
					type="subject">work</term> in the evening, he even made us <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562"
					type="subject">exercise</term>. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Lance
					Sergeant</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_borza">Borza</persName> was a guard to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560"
					type="subject">labour service company</term> no. 101/11 and the whip never rested in his hands. Once we were leaving for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> at 7 am in double quick pace and I tripped
				and fell in the darkness. <persName ref="#ehri_et_borza">Borza</persName> stepped up to me and while shouting that I was a saboteur,
				he <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat</term> me to a pulp. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1077" type="subject">Privates</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_bottka">Bottka</persName> and <persName ref="#ehri_et_botha">Bótha</persName> were also very <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">cruel</term> to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560" type="subject">labour servicemen</term>. Later <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Warrant Officer</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_ligety">Ligety</persName> (of Jewish descent) was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">appointed commander</term> of our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560" type="subject">company.</term> He also committed a series of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">cruel</term> acts. He called upon the guards to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">torture</term> us and every so often he declared that
				on his list of priority number one was the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1077" type="subject"
					>Hungarian soldier</term>, number two was nobody, number three was nobody too and the Jew came only after these: he also said that
				there was no other way to talk to the Jews only by a whip. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886"
					type="subject">Cadet Sergeant</term> Fritz (a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject"
					>counterintelligence officer</term>) took away all of our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836"
					type="subject">clothes</term>. He <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat</term>
				people with a whip; he walked around with a whip in his hand. On <date when="1942-10-22">October 22, 1942</date>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1215" type="subject">partisans</term> attacked the village where we were
				accommodated. Forty-one brothers-in-arms and me joined the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1215"
					type="subject">partisans</term> and fought the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>. I was a
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1215" type="subject">partisan</term> until <date when="1943-11-10"
					>November 10, 1943</date>, then for three months I worked as a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287"
					type="subject">physician</term>. Later I was taken to another civilian <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term>. Later I was sent to a one-month-long
				further training to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/515012/orel.html">Orel</placeName>. I came back to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungary</placeName> with a mixed transport through <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Romania</placeName>.</p>
